{"/service/ndnp/fu/batch_fu_greenville_ver01/data/sn95047212/00529042334/1958041701/0081.xml":{"full_text":"FORTIETH ANNIVERSARY EDITION\nCab or (Citizen\nVol. XXXX\u2014No. 1\nTowle Talks by Chas. F. Towle\nForty Years In Retrospect\nFor the benefit of those readers who may not have seen our\ncolumn of February 13th relative to the founding of the labor paper\nin this area, we are reprinting our column, \u201cForty Years in Retro-\nCentral shared the quarters of Miami Carpenters Local Union\nNo. 993 with other unions existing here at the time. In fact, it was a\ntypical labor \u201changout,\u201d where anything could happen\u2014and usually\ndid. (And of all the old-timers left, if any, I\u2019ll bet a plugged nickel\nA. D. Cain was present at this same meeting.)\nWell, anyway, this particular night E. K. Dahlman led off with\na sizzling remark about the activities of the unions and their mem\nbership being hampered because they were not getting much pub\nlicity in the Herald and the Daily Metropolis (now the Daily News),\n(and where have we heard that plaint before?), and he thought it\nwould be a good idea for Central to start a paper of its own.\nWalter Hoyt, a member of the Teamsters Union, and J. M. Sand\nerson, a union painter, added their bit so successfully that by the\ntime the meeting ended they had been appointed members of a com\nmittee entrusted with the care of an unborn child and making provi\nsions for its future. Central forgot, however, to provide an annuity,\nor even a nursing fund, but that was no deterrent to the first board\nof directors, Dahlman, Hoyt and Sanderson. They immediately en\ngaged Stephen C. Singleton, then a member of Painters Local 365,\nas their first editor. Incidentally, he got paid off mostly in honor,\nbut nevertheless, proved to be a wise selection and did a bang-up\njob, and within three weeks \u201cThe Miami Central News\u201d came out as\na five column folio newspaper breathing pent-up feelings and in-\nspiration.\nThe first publication was produced in a printshop on old Avenue\nD near the FEC switching tracks leading to the Hotel Royal Palm.\nThis shop was operated by \u201cDoc\u201d Cannon and the same E. K. Dahl\nman, who was one of the prime instigators of the project.\nAfter two years of publication by the Miami Central Labor\nUnion, the late Gordon Russell, veteran member of the International\nTypographical Union, took over the paper and became its publisher,\nwith the endorsement of the Miami Central Labor Union as labor\u2019s\nofficial organ, an endorsement which it proudly bears to this date.\nMr. Russell operated his paper until his death on April 24, 1938.\nWalter Hoyt, still associated with the paper as business manager for\nMr. Russell, then purchased the paper, which had become the Miami\nCitizen, a change in name made necessary when James M. Cox pur\nchased the Metropolis and it became the Miami Daily News.\nFollowing the death of Walter Hoyt in the early part of 1948, the\nwriter became the owner in March, and has operated it since that\ntime as the Miami Labor Citizen, and lately as the Labor Citizen.\nSince before Mr. Hoyt acquired the paper, it has been printed\nwith the exception of two short periods of time, by Towle Printers.\nDuring one of those periods, it missed its first and last weekly issue\nfollowing the hurricane of September 18, 1926, when its home at\nthat time, the plant of the Miami Post, was completely wrecked.\nAnd now, as we celebrate our fortieth anniversary, following the\nclosing of Towle Printers, we find it back in the Post plant again.\nMany names appear in the roster of the builders of Miami Labor\nas we con some of the dusty files of yesteryear. Among them just\na few will bring back memories McClurg, Rigby, Bagley, Henry\nRees Johnny Burke, Singleton, Banforth, Hoyt, Singer, Livingston,\nJohnson, Mrs. Roberts, Cliff Hoyt, Dave Kenyon, Horkeimer, Ernie\nOtt, Harold Schuler, F. J. Reed, and many others. Of all those named\nonly Ernie Ott, our former diminutive advertising solicitor, Harold\nSchuler and F. J. Reed are still among the living.\nWhen this paper began publication, there were 14 local unions\nin Miami, a city of less than 20,000 people. And now there are about\n70 locals affiliated with the Central Labor Union, which now is\nknown as the Dade County Federation of Labor, besides a number of\nunaffiliated locals, and Greater Miami has become the largest city in\nFlorida with a population approaching three-quarters of a million.\nOfficial Organ of\nDADE COUNTY FEDERATION OF LABOR, BUILDING TRADES COUNCIL, FLORIDA FEDERATION OF LABOR\nspect.\u201d We hope it will bring back nostalgic memo\nries to many of you.\nI wonder how many readers of this column,\nremember a night in March, 1918, at a meeting in\na small hall on Avenue D, now South Miami Avenue,\non the spot where the Miami Herald now stands,\nwhen a discussion under \u201cgood and welfare\u201d in the\nCentral Labor Union meeting, gave birth to the\npresent Miami Labor Citizen.\nIt was one of those warmish nights in March,\nwhen your Winter clothes begin to itch your skin\nand good old-fashioned sweat begins to ooze from\nactive pores; just the right kind of night to make\none feel like discussing something worthwhile.\nMiami, Florida, Thursday, April 17, 1958\nVeterans Eligible\nFor Fed. Benefits\nTALLAHASSEE\u2014Korean War\nveterans who are now or who may\nbecome unemployed were re\nminded today they may be eligible\nfor federal benefits of $26 a week\nunder the Unemployment Compen\nsation for Veterans program es\ntablished by the Veterans Read\njustment Act of 1952.\nAccording to Charles M. Mann,\nState Director of the Unemploy\nment Compensation division of the\nFlorida Industrial Commission, a\nveteran may qualify for these\nbenefits if he:\n(1) had at least 90 days service\nsome of which occurred between\nJune 27, 1950 and January 31,\n1955.\n(2) has received a discharge\nother than dishonorable.\n(3) has collected less than $676\nin past payments under the fed\neral unemployment compensation\nprogram for veterans and\n(4) has exhausted his state un\nemployment insurance rights, if\nany.\nTo be eligible for a weekly pay\nment up to 26 weeks, the veteran\nmust be unemployed and other\nwise meet the eligibility require\nments of the State Unemployment\nCompensation Law.\nBenefits are payable until July\n26, 1958 or within three years of\nthe veteran\u2019s discharge, whichever\nis later. Benefits are paid by the\nstate with federal funds.\nVeterans applying for benefits\nshould visit their local State Em\nployment Service office, of which\nthere are 35 throughout Florida.\nMeany Asks Speedy Senate Action\nOn Bill To Protect Welfare Funds\nWASHINGTON\u2014Speedy Senate action on the Doug\nlas-Kennedy-Ives bill to protect the pension and welfare\nmoney of millions of workers has been urged by AFL-CIO\nPres. George Meany.\nIn a letter to Senate Democratic Leader Lyndon John-\nson (Tex.), Meany pointed out\nthat the benefits involved in these\nplans now are \u201cextremely large,\u201d\nthat workers \u201crely on these funds\nfor security in their later years,\u201d\nand that prompt congressional ac\ntion to protect the money is \u201cvital\nand necessary.\u201d\nThe bill has been reported fa\nvorable by an overwhelming ma\njority of the Senate Labor and\nPublic Welfare Committee, the\nAFL-CIO president noted, and he\nasked Johnson as Senate majority\nleader to schedule the bill for floor\naction \u201cas soon as possible.\u201d\nJohnson promptly replied with\nan indication of a green light for\nthe measure.\n\u201cI believe,\u201d he wrote Meany,\n\u201cthat this measure should be\npassed without crippling amend\nments and certainly I will do what\nI can to achieve that objective.\u201d\nThe Douglas-Kennedy-Ives bill\nwould require the administrators\nof all large employe welfare and\npension plans to file with.the Fed\neral government financial reports\ndisclosing their stewardship. It\nwould also make false statements\nand embezzlement of the funds in\nvolved federal criminal offenses.\nMeany observed that welfare\nplan administration had been thor\noughly investigated by Senate sub\ncommittees headed in 1954-55 by\nSen. Paul H. Douglas (D-Ill.) and\nSen. Irving M. Ives (R-N.Y.) and\nthat legislative remedies to correct\nReports Show Record High\nPostwar Unemployment Rate\nWASHINGTON\u2014The nation\u2019s economy continued\nits downward slide in March as the worst recession since\nthe end of World War II produced new record unemploy-\nment figures.\nGovernment reports ind\nadded to the jobless rolls, a sharp' 1\nreversal of the normal drop of\n200,000 in unemployment in mid-\nMarch.\nEmployment increased about\n323,000 from mid-February to\nmid-March in contrast with a nor\nmal increase of about 500,000 at\nthe start of the spring season.\nThe result: the rate of unem\nployment rose from 6.7 percent to\n7 percent, a new postwar high.\nAFL-CIO Pres. George Meany\nsaid the figures in the joint report\nof the Labor and Commerce Depts,\n\u201cindicate a continued deepening\nof the recession. There is nothing\nto indicate that the recession\nhas hit bottom, let alone any sign\nof a pick-up.\u201d\nHe added: \u201cThere is nothing\nthat we in the AFL-CIO would\nwelcome more than an end to this\nrecession. But facts are facts and\nthere isn\u2019t a single ray of sun\nshine\u201d in the report.\n\u201cThe only way to change the\nsituation is for the government to\nact now. Optimistic press releases\nwon\u2019t end this recession but legis\nlation can.\u201d\nThe White House, however,\nclaimed that the figures indicated\na \u201cslowing up of the decline,\u201d and\nLabor Sec. Mitchell in a statement\nfor the newsreels termed the fig-\nabuses had been the subject of\nhearings by a subcommittee of\nwhich Sen. John F. Kennedy\n(D-Mass.) was chairman.\nThe Douglas-Ives investigations\nrevealed some abuses in the man\nagement of welfare-and-pension\n(Continued on Page 8)\nFCC Asked to Investigate\nNAM Sponsorship of\nProbe Broadcasts\nWASHINGTON AFL CIO\nPres. George Meany has sent the\nfollowing telegram to FCC Chair\nman John C. Doerfer:\n\u201cThe AFL-CIO is deeply con\ncerned over the action of the Na\ntional Association of Manufactur\ners in purchasing kinescopic sum\nmaries of each day\u2019s Kohler hear\nings and making them available\nfor television broadcasting without\npublic disclosure of the origin of\nthe films.\n\u201cYour regulations wisely pro\nvide that stations shall identify\nthose who furnish any program\ninvolving the discussion of public\ncontroversial issues and we believe\nthat the arrangements of the\nNAM with the stations violated\nboth the letter and the spirit of\nthese regulations. We trust you\nwill treat this telegram as a for\nmal complaint and institute an\nimmediate investigation of this\nmatter.\u201d\n7\nicated at least 25,000 were\nures \u201cencouraging\u201d and that the\nnation\u2019s economy is \u201cbasically\nsound.\u201d\nThe 323,000 rise in employment\nwas concentrated in farm labor\nand construction contrasting with\nthe 200,000 drop in manufactur\ning, a much greater than seasonal\ndecline.\nJobs in manufacturing were\ndown by 1,590,090 from a year\nago and non-farm employment\nwas 1,749,000 below the March,\n1957, figures.\nThe government report showed\nalso that:\nThe number of persons out of\nwork 15 weeks or longer rose\nsharply by 300,000 to a postwar\nrecord of 1,446,000.\nThe number of persons working\na short week was up 200,000 to\n2,2*90,000. The average factory\nwork week was unchanged from\nFebruary at 38.5 hours and weekly\nwages averaged about the same as\nthe preceding month but were\n$1.35 down from a year ago.\nState insured unemployment\nshowed a continued increase in 33\nstates in March with the national\nrate moving from 7.5 to 7.8 per\ncent.\nNine stated had unemployment\nexceeding 10 percent, including\nMichigan with 14 percent and\nKentucky, West Virginia and Mon\ntana with more than 12 percent.\nA separate Labor Dept, report\nshowed that Negro workers had\nbeen hit much harder by the reces\nsion than white workers with the\nnon-white rate of unemployment\nrunning 16 percent compared to 7\nfor white workers.\nThe report noted also that about\nhalf of the nation\u2019s jobless in Feb\nruary were married men.\nCalls National\nConference On\nWorkmen\u2019^ Comp.\nWASHINGTON A National\nConference on Workmen\u2019s Com\npensation, sponsored by the AFL\nCIO, opens April 15, at the Shera\nton-Park Hotel here to promote\nlabor\u2019s safety and health goals,\npoint up the need for improving\nmedical services and rehabilitation\nand to advocate adequate and\nprompt benefit payments.\nThese three topics head the list\nfor discussion along with elimina\ntion of costly and wasteful litiga\ntion and adequate insurance at\nminimal dollar cost. Besides dis\ncussions for revising workmen\u2019s\ncompensation in the United States\nthe conference will mark the fifti\neth anniversary of the beginning\nof workmen\u2019s compensation at a\ndinner on April 16 featuring an\naddress by AFL-CIO Sec.-Treas.\nWilliam F. Schnitzler on \u201cWork\nmen\u2019s Compensation, 50 Years in\nReview.\u201d\nDelegates from all national and\ninternational unions, state central\nbodies and departments of the\nAFL-CIO will attend the confer\nence which is scheduled to hold\nthree days of sessions.\nNelson H. Cruikshank, director\n(Continued on Page 8)\nPrice: Five Cents","height":"27519","width":"18735"}}
